332, +more)]\\n\\nThe relationship data reinforces this centrality by repeatedly attaching key components and sub-investigations directly to Activity 3 (meter ruler equilibrium, moment dependence investigation, friction surface-area investigation, and multiple diagrams/tables). The resulting community structure is therefore “Activity 3–centric,” with instruments and figures serving as supporting entities rather than independent hubs. [Data: Relationships (2346, 2374, 2271, 1351, 1336, +more)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Force addition and equilibrium are demonstrated using three Newton balances and a strip-of-wood setup\",\"explanation\":\"One major mechanics component of Activity 3 is a verification that the resultant of two parallel forces equals their sum, using a strip of wood with holes (X, Y, Z) and three Newton balances (A, B, C). The key observation described is that the readings on balances A and B add up to the reading on balance C when the strip is at rest (equilibrium). [Data: Entities (1029, 1374, 1375, 1385); Relationships (1971, 1953)]\\n\\nThe entities specify distinct roles for Newton balances A, B, and C in this equilibrium condition: A and B provide forces whose combined effect is balanced by C, and C’s reading equals the resultant of A and B in the described setup. The relationship linking B to C further encodes this equilibrium logic (C equals the resultant of A and B) and situates it as a measured, instrument-based demonstration rather than a purely theoretical claim. [Data: Entities (1374, 1375, 1385); Relationships (1953, 1971, 1969)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Equilibrium of three parallel, coplanar forces is illustrated with a meter ruler suspended by spring balances and rubber bands\",\"explanation\":\"Activity 3 also addresses equilibrium of three parallel, coplanar forces using a meter ruler as the rigid body. The ruler is suspended at both ends using spring balances and rubber bands, and learners compare the ruler’s weight to the sum of the upward balance readings to verify equilibrium conditions. [Data: Entities (1029, 1576, 1577, 1578, 1593); Relationships (2346, 2349, 2350, 2374)]\\n\\nFigures associated with the activity (notably Figure 12.10) depict this suspended meter-ruler arrangement and tie the conceptual requirement—one force opposing the other two, with resultants balancing—to a concrete measurement setup. The network indicates the meter ruler is central to this sub-experiment, with spring balances providing the quantitative upward forces and rubber bands acting as the connectors enabling suspension and adjustment to a horizontal equilibrium. [Data: Entities (1589, 1576, 1577, 1578, 1593); Relationships (2364, 2349, 2350, 2346)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Moments/torque dependence on perpendicular distance is operationalized via a constant-force Newton balance and recorded in Table 11.3\",\"explanation\":\"Activity 3 includes an investigation of how moment depends on the perpendicular distance (lever arm) from a pivot/point of suspension. The described procedure keeps the applied force constant while varying the position at which the Newton balance applies the force, observing when rotation begins as a clamp/screw is tightened in steps. [Data: Entities (1029, 1533, 1539, 1540); Relationships (2271, 2296, 2297)]\\n\\nThe dataset includes a concrete results table (Table 11.3) indicating a constant force (1.5 N) alongside increasing distances (e.g., 15 cm, 32 cm, 55 cm) required to initiate rotation under different tightening conditions (initial, quarter turn, half turn). This anchors the investigation as measurement-driven and provides an explicit artifact for comparing conditions, while Figure 11.5 documents the geometry (varying distances x1, x2, x3 from pivot O). [Data: Entities (1540, 1539, 1533); Relationships (2297, 2296, 2271)]\"},{\"summary\":\"Limiting friction is tested against contact area using a single wooden block with different faces (Figure 5.4)\",\"explanation\":\"A distinct Activity 3 investigatio